Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to ensure that:
The Municipal Accountant, Inventory Committee and GSO identify the variances of PPE account balances between the accounting records and the result of the physical count, and reconcile such variances to facilitate the proper recording/reporting of PPE account balances in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The Management prioritize the provision of additional manpower or other strategies to assist the GSO in completing a physical count of PPE and inventories;
The Inventory Committee conduct inventory taking activities according to previously approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and prepare the RPCPPE upon completion of the physical count, using the prescribed format under the Accounting Manual and submit the same not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;
The GSO prepare and maintain property cards for each PPE and reconcile the same with the accounting records and the result of the physical count; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete PPELCs, and reconcile the same with the property records and the results of the physical count.

Management Comment
The current GSO is a newly-designated personnel and had just assumed office sometime in November 2024, hence the inventory/physical count of the properties was not completed. Further, the newly-designated GSO has not been trained fully as to the scope of its work, including the reportorial requirements and activities that need to be done regularly. However, the Management concurs with the observation and commits to comply with the recommendations.

Recommendation
We recommended and the LCE agreed to ensure that the Municipal Accountant:
Present the computation and breakdown of interest paid per loan agreements for CY 2024;
Investigate the discrepancies in LDRRM Utilization report and LDRRM Trust Liability and prepare adjusting entries if needed and/or provide the accurate LDRRM utilization report;
Take corrective actions to accurately present the Net Cash Flows and Operating Activities to Surplus by reconstructing the Cash Flow Statement, if needed; and
Prepare a comprehensive and accurate reconciliation report addressing the discrepancies identified between the SCBAA and SFPer balances, with all variances clearly explained and the final report aligned with both sources.

Recommendations
We recommended and Management agreed that through the Municipal Engineer:
At the beginning of each year, provide the Office of the Auditor with a comprehensive inventory of all active PPAs as well as those that are scheduled for implementation throughout the year;
Submit to COA the quarterly monitoring report on the implementation of the PPAs using the template prescribed in the above-mentioned Circular. Also include the information as to the mode of procurement and status of the project such as on-going, for implementation, completed, suspended/ cancelled, terminated and for bidding;
Upload the quarterly monitoring report in the LGU’s website as part of its Transparency Seal; and
In every project site, the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices should be installed to apprise the public of project details.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
Adapt and maintain the asset method of recording the inventory items and require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the proper implementation of the perpetual inventory method of recording all inventory items to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials. They may request storage facilities and install proper and stringent internal control on the acceptance, inspection and issuance of inventories;
Maintain a special account for the Rubber Trading Program where inventories from agricultural produce held for sale are properly recorded and monitored, to determine its viability;
Determine whether the reported balances, which remained non-moving from beginning to end, are actually on hand and existing and do the necessary corrections in the books; and
Require department heads/ end-users accountable for inventories to maintain stock cards for all stocks and regularly update, monitor, balance and reconcile the stock cards against stocks on hand.

Recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed through the Sanggunian Bayan to instruct the:
Municipal Budget Officer and other responsible offices to prepare and submit Annual Operating Budget (AOB) for each LEEs that is supported by a BP and SAFSSR;
Local Finance committee (LFC) or Economic Development Officer if any, to deliberate and prepare a 5-year Business Plan (BP) especially with the newly established LEEs;
LFC to conduct semi-annual review and general examination of cost and accomplishments against performance standards.

Recommendations:
To fortify the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Instruct the PSCP committee and working group to prioritize the formulation of the municipal PSCP in accordance with the PSCP guidebook and thereafter submit the plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP;
Direct the HRMO to further enhance the Municipal Capacity Development agenda by incorporating other mandatory training on Public Service Continuity Planning and ensuring participation of the appropriate LGU officials and personnel in the same; and,
Improve monitoring of operational requirements like the formulation and submission of PSCP to the relevant oversight bodies;

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:

Require all officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances immediately;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
Established measures to enforce immediate liquidation of outstanding cash advances to be enacted such as sending demand letter to the accountable officer or effect deduction from salaries/benefits due to the concerned employee;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert all efforts to expedite liquidation of cash advances of officers and employees who have resigned or no longer in service; and
Enhance the Municipality’s record keeping and controls through providing sufficient and appropriate storage and IT Infrastructure.

We recommended that:

Municipal Accountant perform a detailed review and analysis of the affected accounts and prepare the necessary correcting journal entry vouchers to have a fair presentation of the accounts in the financial statements and to prepare and maintain CIP Ledger Cards (CIPLCs) on a per project basis and to effect the transfer of completed projects from the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts and ensure that proper accounts are used in recording transactions;

Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accounting Office with copies of the report of completed projects and other necessary documents;

Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile inventory records; and

Inventory committee created thru an issuance of a written order complete the actual physical count on a specified time frame and submit complete physical inventory report in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommend that Management should improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

